# WITNESSED live on a real Pi 4: core.autocrlf=true (this Windows clone's
# default) silently converted kernel/rt-tune.sh's line endings to CRLF the
# moment it was edited and re-committed, corrupting the deployed script on
# Alpine/busybox ash (`#!/bin/sh\r` breaks the shebang lookup, and every
# line's trailing \r merges into the next token -- "illegal option -",
# ": not found"). This silently broke the boot-time RT tuning (the
# performance-governor pin) with no error anywhere in the pipeline: CI
# stayed green (nothing there runs the script), the packaging step
# (image/lib-boot-tree.sh) just copies bytes, and the failure only ever
# surfaced as a real device behaving wrong. Force LF for every text format
# actually consumed by a shell/POSIX interpreter, regardless of what any
# individual clone's core.autocrlf is set to -- this is a repo-wide
# correctness requirement, not a per-developer preference.
* text=auto eol=lf

*.sh text eol=lf
*.start text eol=lf
*.conf text eol=lf
*.yml text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf
Makefile text eol=lf
cmdline.txt text eol=lf
config.txt text eol=lf
usercfg.txt text eol=lf

# Binaries must never be touched by line-ending normalization at all.
*.so binary
*.bin binary
*.dtb binary
*.dtbo binary
*.elf binary
*.exe binary
*.wav binary
*.tar.gz binary
*.zip binary
